-----------------

# Git Standards

Primary branch: `main`.

Do not force-push to `main`.

---

# Commit Frequency

* Create commits only when explicitly requested.
* Prefer one logical change per commit.
* Do not bundle unrelated changes together.
* Do not commit work that fails validation.
* Do not create empty commits.

---

# Commit Requirements

Every commit must:

* be scoped to an active plan or explicitly authorized work;
* pass validation (or bootstrap validation exception applies);
* exclude secrets and local artifacts;
* include documentation updates when architecture or behavior changes.

Never commit:

```text
.env
.venv/
.pytest_cache/
.ruff_cache/
__pycache__/
```

Never commit:

* credentials;
* API keys;
* local configuration files;
* temporary debugging code;
* commented-out experiments.

---

# Validation Requirements

Before commit (required after Python bootstrap):

```bash
uv run ruff format --check .
uv run ruff check .
uv run basedpyright
uv run pytest
```

Validation failures must be resolved before commit.

### Bootstrap Validation Exception

**Status:** Superseded (Python bootstrap completed — see `docs/PROGRESS.md`).

Before `pyproject.toml` existed, documentation-only commits were exempt from the quality commands above.

Standard validation is now mandatory for all commits.

---

# Commit Message Format

Use Conventional Commits.

Format:

```text
<type>(<scope>): <summary>

[optional body]

[optional footer]
```

Example:

```text
feat(agent): add tool routing node
```

Example:

```text
feat(mcp): add search_documents tool
```

Example:

```text
fix(retrieval): preserve reranker ordering
```

Example:

```text
docs(architecture): document retrieval pipeline
```

---

# Allowed Commit Types

| Type     | Purpose                     |
| -------- | --------------------------- |
| feat     | New capability              |
| fix      | Bug fix                     |
| docs     | Documentation-only change   |
| test     | Test-only change            |
| refactor | Internal restructuring      |
| chore    | Tooling and maintenance     |
| ci       | CI/CD changes               |
| build    | Packaging and build changes |

---

# Commit Message Rules

Subject line:

* imperative mood;
* lowercase after prefix;
* no trailing period;
* maximum 72 characters.

Use a scope whenever practical.

Preferred scopes:

```text
agent
mcp
retrieval
indexing
storage
llm
architecture
repo
tests
docs
```

The commit body should explain:

```text
Why
```

rather than:

```text
What
```

when the reason is not obvious.

---

# Branching Strategy

`main` is the integration branch.

Create feature branches from `main`.

Examples:

```text
feat/hybrid-retrieval
feat/mcp-server
feat/indexing-pipeline
```

Keep branches:

* short-lived;
* focused;
* aligned with a single plan.

Do not force-push to `main`.

Force-push feature branches only when coordinated and intentional.

---

# Plans and Commits

Implementation commits must remain within active-plan scope.

If the relationship is not obvious, reference the plan:

```text
Plan: docs/plans/completed/02-python-bootstrap.md
```

in the commit body.

Update:

```text
docs/PROGRESS.md
```

when completing meaningful milestones.

Move completed plans to:

```text
docs/plans/completed/
```

when work finishes.

No implementation without plan authorization.

---

# Architecture Changes

Non-trivial architecture changes require:

* documentation updates;
* ADR entries in docs/DECISIONS.md.

Examples:

* LangGraph architecture changes;
* MCP contract changes;
* retrieval architecture changes;
* indexing architecture changes;
* source attribution design changes;
* LLM integration changes.

Architecture should not exist only in source code.

---

# Documentation Changes

Documentation is part of the implementation.

Update documentation when changing:

* architecture;
* retrieval behavior;
* indexing behavior;
* MCP contracts;
* source attribution;
* project scope.

Relevant documents include:

```text
PROJECT.md
docs/ARCHITECTURE.md
docs/DECISIONS.md
docs/PROGRESS.md
```

Documentation changes should be committed alongside the related implementation whenever practical.

---

# Refactoring

Refactoring must not change observable behavior.

Use:

```text
refactor(<scope>):
```

Keep refactors:

* focused;
* reviewable;
* independent from feature development.

Avoid drive-by refactors outside active-plan scope.

Run the full validation suite after refactoring.

---

# Temporary Code

Remove before commit:

* debugging helpers;
* scratch scripts;
* temporary experiments;
* validation bypasses.

Avoid committing unfinished scaffolding.

---

# Generated Files

Commit:

* `uv.lock`;
* required reproducible dependency artifacts.

Do not commit:

* caches;
* bytecode;
* local environments;
* temporary outputs.

If generated files must be tracked, document the reason.

---

# Before Push Checklist

Before pushing:

1. Review `git status`.
2. Review `git diff`.
3. Confirm validation passes.
4. Confirm documentation updates are included.
5. Confirm commit messages follow conventions.
6. Confirm branch is up to date with `main`.
7. Do not push unless explicitly requested.

---

# Definition of a Good Commit

A good commit:

* solves one logical problem;
* delivers one plan increment;
* leaves the repository in a working state;
* passes validation (or bootstrap validation exception applies);
* has a clear commit message;
* explains why when needed;
* stays within active-plan scope;
* contains no secrets or local artifacts;
* includes required documentation updates.

Every commit should be understandable without opening the entire diff.
